    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "MACRS depreciation for a 7-year property class is a straightforward process. The formula is: \n\nDepreciation = (Cost - Residual Value) / Useful Life\n\nFor a 7-year property class, the useful life is 7 years. Since you didn't specify the residual value, let's assume it's 0 for simplicity. \n\nThe formula becomes: Depreciation = Cost / 7\n\nFor the first year, the depreciation is simply the full cost of the equipment, as it's considered 100% depreciable in the first year. This is a common practice in the manufacturing industry, where equipment is often fully depreciated in the first year due to its high initial cost.\n\nTo calculate the depreciation for the first year, you can use the following formula:\n\nYear 1 Depreciation = Cost / 1\n\nSo, if the cost of the equipment is $100,000, the depreciation for the first year would be $100,000. \n\nKeep in mind that this is just a simplified example, and actual depreciation calculations may vary depending on your specific situation and local tax laws. It's always best to consult with a tax professional or accountant for accurate guidance.",
